<paragraph id="13666FA0DBFD7118A989B91FCD253926" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
QMG329976 (SBD513022), south of Rock Cod Shoal, off Gladstone, Great Barrier Reef, 23.725°S; 151.6647°E, 34 m depth, epibenthic sled, coll. FRV 'Lady 
<normalizedToken id="6AA696A49EB4CDE4BE18C7667095C322" originalValue="Basten’">Basten'</normalizedToken>
, 20 September 2004.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66C919FC22B3227E29BED308B5D77FE7" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="E5EEAACF300415C24767352107F304D4" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="38E4EA4CF9366418D04E4D178EDD7E42" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
(from 
<bibRefCitation id="F8D2839D20F6E0C42CF6549F13FC8B6B" author="Sutcliffe, PR" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 30" title="The most common sponges on the Great Barrier Reef seabed, Australia, include species new to science (Phylum Porifera)." volume="2616" year="2010">Sutcliffe et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). A thin sponge agglutinating biogenic rubble such as remains of worm tubes, gastropods and bivalves. Usually fist-sized or smaller. Live color red to yellow, surface uneven, no visible oscules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B6506FEB407898FA33D145E92857AA50" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spicules: three-claded calthrops and sanidasters.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9AC4777C06D4370281F514ADD6E8A76D" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Calthrops small, divisible in two size classes with means of approximately 25 and 72 
<normalizedToken id="B79E76CA05BF26CFADFB6FD0A8B22E0E" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. Only 20% of the 163 specimens recorded possessed calthrops, usually in high densities, in the remaining 80 % these spicules were lacking. Sanidasters universally present in all specimens, displaying a wide variation in length and width, 10-20 
<normalizedToken id="0F3B1B1572D8E53B2EA8322FBBBD7952" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2.5 
<normalizedToken id="9D11EC14540066B876DDC9C66FDF77E6" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, densely spined with relatively short spines up to 1 
<normalizedToken id="5AA6DD9B3733F21854E9E0101B794AB2" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49A775E92398C5B99E3A78C0D4AAA443" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="E6C24E5E318491666BD5D746034D11B2" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6663BCF6168422DFB160177A5BAF3B2E" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sandy bottoms between 16 and 86 m depth.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C7F722A8DD99200B95D700194F93FC0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="3FCD2553D179AC81512779D61D7C95E2" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15D18B3C979EAE15AB5A15CD3A3C7729" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Great Barrier Reef, occurring over the entire range.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3CE15DD1D99186E0EAADF1A5622FD0C6" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="2918E1D918A0ED445A44B9AE2A3495E0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A93D97CA164FB7FD9870440856B890B3" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
As 
<bibRefCitation id="48A604AD34B83D9838EA4271E8150F98" author="Sutcliffe, PR" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 30" title="The most common sponges on the Great Barrier Reef seabed, Australia, include species new to science (Phylum Porifera)." volume="2616" year="2010">Sutcliffe et al. (2010)</bibRefCitation>
point out, there is only one species among the 
<taxonomicName id="2306C01AF425B635A37C47A936A00ACB" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Dercitus</taxonomicName>
s.l. species that is similar, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="8F30344542D6DCA734202D6B7372A01A" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus (Stoeba) syrmatitus" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="syrmatitus" subGenus="Stoeba">Dercitus (Stoeba) syrmatitus</taxonomicName>
, sharing the possession of three-claded calthrops, the small size of the calthrops and the agglutinating habit. The differences are nevertheless quite clear and compelling, the rarity of the megascleres, the lack of normal fourc-claded calthrops and the distinctly larger sanidasters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="45D7BD1D94024BDCE19327F722D80155" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
The only other Australian record of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="E9321385F30855A8EF5F1432658A32A1" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Dercitus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dercitus (Stoeba) occultus" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="occultus" subGenus="Stoeba">Dercitus (Stoeba) occultus</taxonomicName>
, from West Australia, differs sharply in having exclusively dichocalthrops megascleres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
